2026-07-21 | Maximum Absolute Difference Between Two Non-Overlapping Subarrays

	Question
Return the maximum possible absolute difference between the sums of two non-overlapping contiguous subarrays.
	Key Insight
For every possible split of the array, the two subarrays must lie on opposite sides of the split.
So we precompute four arrays:
	leftMax[i]
	= Maximum subarray sum in the range [0...i].
	leftMin[i]
	= Minimum subarray sum in the range [0...i].
	rightMax[i]
	= Maximum subarray sum in the range [i...n−1].
	rightMin[i]
	= Minimum subarray sum in the range [i...n−1].
These arrays can all be computed using Kadane's algorithm.
For every split between indices i and i+1, there are only two possibilities:
	1.
		Large positive on the left
		Large negative on the right
		leftMax[i] − rightMin[i+1]
	2.
		Large negative on the left
		Large positive on the right
		rightMax[i+1] − leftMin[i]
The maximum of these over all splits is the answer.
	Approach
1.	Compute leftMax using Kadane from left to right.
2.	Compute leftMin using modified Kadane for minimum sums.
3.	Compute rightMax from right to left.
4.	Compute rightMin from right to left.
5.	For every split between i and i+1:
		- Compute:
				leftMax[i] − rightMin[i+1]
		- Compute:
				rightMax[i+1] − leftMin[i]
		- Update the answer.
6.	Return the maximum value.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int maxAbsDifference(vector<int>& arr) {
        int n = arr.size();
        vector<int> leftMax(n), leftMin(n);
        vector<int> rightMax(n), rightMin(n);
        int curMax = arr[0];
        leftMax[0] = arr[0];
        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            curMax = max(arr[i], curMax + arr[i]);
            leftMax[i] = max(leftMax[i - 1], curMax);
        }
        int curMin = arr[0];
        leftMin[0] = arr[0];
        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            curMin = min(arr[i], curMin + arr[i]);
            leftMin[i] = min(leftMin[i - 1], curMin);
        }
        curMax = arr[n - 1];
        rightMax[n - 1] = arr[n - 1];
        for(int i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            curMax = max(arr[i], curMax + arr[i]);
            rightMax[i] = max(rightMax[i + 1], curMax);
        }
        curMin = arr[n - 1];
        rightMin[n - 1] = arr[n - 1];
        for(int i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            curMin = min(arr[i], curMin + arr[i]);
            rightMin[i] = min(rightMin[i + 1], curMin);
        }
        int ans = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
            ans = max(ans, abs(leftMax[i] - rightMin[i + 1]));
            ans = max(ans, abs(rightMax[i + 1] - leftMin[i]));
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
	Example
	Input:
		arr = [1, 2, -3, 1]
	leftMax:
		[1, 3, 3, 3]
	leftMin:
		[1, 1, -3, -3]
	rightMax:
		[3, 2, 1, 1]
	rightMin:
		[-3, -3, -3, 1]
	Checking every split gives the maximum absolute difference:
		6
	Output:
		6
	Key Insight
	The two subarrays must be separated by some split point. By precomputing the maximum and minimum subarray sums on both the left and right sides of every split using Kadane's algorithm, each split can be evaluated in constant time. This results in an optimal **O(n)** solution.
